## Context

Ticket 0028 builds the beat dashboard's Views 1 and 2. This ticket adds View 3: a cross-project
blocker graph rendered as inline SVG, served at `/blockers`.

The graph surfaces "keystone" tickets — those blocking multiple chains across projects — which
are worth prioritising even when they appear individually small.

## Scope constraint

The `.erg` `Blocked-by:` header supports intra-project ticket IDs (`0031`) and GitHub issue refs
(`gh#N`). It does NOT support cross-repo ticket references. View 3 therefore operates on
intra-project edges only. A node is drawn for every open/doing/pending ticket that appears in any
`Blocked-by` header or has one. `gh#N` blockers are rendered as grey terminal nodes labeled
`gh#N` with no further resolution.

## Actions

### Layout algorithm (no external lib)
- Build adjacency list: for each ticket, collect its `Blocked-by` refs as outgoing edges
  (edge direction: dependency → dependent, i.e. "A blocks B" → arrow from A to B).
- Topological sort the DAG. Tickets with no outgoing edges (no blockers) sit at depth 0;
  each ticket sits one level deeper than its deepest dependency.
- Assign x-coordinates by depth (column), y-coordinates by index within column. Spacing:
  `col_width = 160px`, `row_height = 50px`. Origin at `(40, 40)`.
- Render as `<svg>` with:
  - `<line>` elements for edges (drawn first, underneath nodes)
  - `<circle r="18">` for ticket nodes, filled by readiness colour
  - `<text>` showing ticket ID centered in circle; font-size 9px
  - Arrowhead via `<marker>` element (standard SVG marker pattern)
- Colour scheme: ready=#22c55e, doing=#3b82f6, blocked=#f97316, pending=#475569, gh#N=#94a3b8

### Route
- `GET /blockers` — render full page with the SVG, legend, and back link to `/`.
- If no tickets have any `Blocked-by` headers, render a page with the message "No blockers found."
  rather than an empty SVG.
- SVG `width` and `height` computed from the layout bounding box + 80px padding each side.

### Data loading
- Reuse `load_tickets(project)` from 0028's implementation.
- Aggregate tickets across all projects. Prefix IDs with project name in tooltip
  (`title` attribute on `<circle>`) to disambiguate same-numbered tickets across projects.
  Node label still shows bare ID (space is tight).

## Test

```bash
# Red step: /blockers returns HTML with an <svg> element when blockers exist
python - <<'EOF'
import urllib.request, subprocess, time, signal, os

PORT = 18766
srv = subprocess.Popen(
    ["python", "bin/beat-dashboard", "--no-browser", "--port", str(PORT),
     "--projects", os.path.expanduser("~/.claude")],
    stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL,
)
time.sleep(1.5)
try:
    body = urllib.request.urlopen(f"http://127.0.0.1:{PORT}/blockers").read().decode()
    assert "<svg" in body, "<svg> element missing from /blockers"
    assert "0028" in body or "No blockers" in body, "neither graph nor empty-state message found"
    print("PASS")
finally:
    srv.send_signal(signal.SIGINT)
EOF
```

## Exit criteria

- `GET /blockers` returns 200 in all cases (never 500).
- When `~/.claude/tickets/0028-multiproject-beat-dashboard.erg` exists with
  `Blocked-by: 0027` (or any open ticket), the SVG contains a `<circle>` for each referenced ID.
  Verify: `curl -s http://127.0.0.1:8765/blockers | grep -o 'circle' | wc -l` ≥ 2.
- When no tickets have `Blocked-by` headers, page body contains "No blockers".
- `gh#N` refs appear as grey terminal nodes, not as a crash or missing node.
- Cycles (ticket A blocked-by B, B blocked-by A) do not cause infinite recursion — the topological
  sort must detect and break cycles, logging a warning to stderr rather than crashing.
- `ruff check bin/beat-dashboard` still clean after this addition.
- SVG is valid: `python -c "import xml.etree.ElementTree as ET; ET.parse(...)"` parses without error.
